SALMONELLOSIS, ALFALFA SPROUTS - USA (NORTHWEST) (02): BACKGROUND
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Sat 5 Jun 2004
From: Steve Berger <Tel@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: GideonOnline.com [edited]


A chronology of salmonellosis outbreaks in the USA associated with sprouts
-----------------------------------------------
1995 to 1996 - An outbreak of _Salmonella_ Newport infection from
December 1995 to January 1996 involved 133 cases in British Columbia
and Oregon (US) and was traced to contaminated alfalfa sprouts.
1995 - 242 cases of serotype Stanley infection were ascribed to
alfalfa sprouts.
1996 - Over 500 cases of serotypes Montivideo and Meleagridis
infection were ascribed to alfalfa sprouts.
1997 - An international outbreak (242 cases in the United States and
Finland) of _Salmonella_ serotype Stanley was traced to alfalfa
sprouts and involved at least 17 states.
1997 - An outbreak of serotypes Infantis and Anatum infection (109
cases) was also attributed to alfalfa sprouts.
1997 to 1998 - A mixture of alfalfa and clover sprouts was implicated
in an outbreak of 60 cases of salmonellosis in California.
1998 - 18 cases of salmonellosis were associated with alfalfa sprouts
in California.
1998 - A multistate outbreak (34 cases) of serotypes Havana, Cubana,
and Tennessee infection was ascribed to alfalfa sprouts.
1998 - A nationwide outbreak (188 cases, 40 hospitalized) of serotype
Agona infection was ascribed to toasted oat cereal products.
1999 - An outbreak (89 cases) of serotype Mbandaka in Oregon,
Washington state, and California was ascribed to alfalfa sprouts
grown in California.
1999 - 175 cases of serotype Muenchen infection were recorded during
a multistate salmonellosis outbreak traced to alfalfa sprouts.
1999 - Clover sprouts were implicated in cases of salmonellosis in
California (30 cases) and in Colorado (70 cases).
2000 - Raw mung-bean spouts were responsible for 45 cases of serotype
Enteritidis infection in California.
2001 - An outbreak (32 cases) of serotype Kottbus infection in
Arizona, California, Colorado, and New Mexico was ascribed to
contaminated alfalfa sprouts.
--
Dr. Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
